TikTok hides unwanted videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18
Imagine China / Reuters
Chinese social network TikTok censored videos that mentions Tiananmen Square, Tibet’s independence or a banned Falun Gong religious group, the Guardian says.
The documents that found out to the publication, it is said that the owner of TikTok (EconteDance) using the application promotes the goals of China’s foreign policy abroad.
Most of the violations relating to China’s policy fall under “hate.”
In each case, TikTok places unwanted publications in a context that fits the general rules so that the social network’s actions do not look censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of the socialist system of China falls under the general ban “criticism or attacks on the policies and social rules of any country, such as a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary system, etc. d."
The ban on mentioning incidents in Tiananmen Square or genocide in Cambodia falls under the “distortion of the history of China or other countries.”
The document also cites a list of banned names of twenty “foreign leaders or statesmen” including North Korean leaders Kim Jong-il, Kim Il-Sung and Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, American presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Park Geun-hee, Indonesian President Joko Widodo and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi.
The banned material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Publications from the first category are deleted by the administrators of the social network and can result in the user blocking.
Not too strict violations fall into the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited to TikTok algorithms.
Representatives of ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer applied: "Now we use a localized approach for moderation, and also attract independent local specialists."
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publications, says the co-founder of the "Producer Center" Rustem Bogdanov.
"Producer Center" - one Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All promotional materials of bloggers "Producer Center" coordinates with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be placed without coordination, Bogdanov reports.
When asked whether it is possible to speak about politics or Putin in TikTok, Bogdanov answers in the affirmative and says that he saw such publications.
The founder of the agency Our Didittal Roman Zaripov agrees with Bogdanov: "The main rules for users TikTok list in the user agreement: you can not post shocking content, discriminatory statements and so on."
But under these rules, you can bring any content that moderators do not like, Zaripov notes.
Zaripov Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18.
According to the user agreement, only persons over the age of 13 can use TikTok.
The administrators of the social network check their age with the help of artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes the faces and determines how many years a person looks, says Bogdanov.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019. ByteDance has opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork coworking.
